{{Infobox monarch | name = Abba Jobir | title = [[King]] of the [[Kingdom of Jimma]] | image = | caption = | reign = 1932 | coronation = | full name = Moti Abba Jobir | predecessor = [[Abba Jifar II]] | successor = | dynasty = [[Kingdom of Jimma]] | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | religion = }}
Moti '''Abba Jobir Abba Dula''' is a member of the [[Oromo people]] who was King of the [[Gibe region|Gibe]] [[Kingdom of Jimma]] (reigned 1932). He was the grandson of [[Abba Jifar II]]. He aligned himself and the [[Oromo people]] and served fascist Italian occupation of Ethiopia.
==Reign== When Abba Jifar II grew senile in his later years, Abba Jobir attempted to seize the throne of the Kingdom of Jimma. However, Emperor [[Haile Selassie]] responded quickly and sent military forces against Abba Jobir. They brought him back to [[Addis Ababa]], where he was imprisoned.<ref>Paul B. Henze, ''Layers of Time, A History of Ethiopia'' (New York: Palgrave, 2000), p. 208</ref>
Following the [[Second Italo-Abyssinian War|Italian invasion]], Abba Jobir was made Governor over part of the [[Italian East Africa]] province of [[Galla-Sidamo]]. He proved useful to the occupiers, helping with Italian propaganda broadcasts to the [[Arabic language|Arabic]]-speaking world. In return, they allowed him a bodyguard of ten armed men, a privilege given to few Ethiopian potentates during the occupation.<ref>Alberto Sbacchi, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/217347 "Italy and the Treatment of the Ethiopian Aristocracy, 1937-1940", ''International Journal of African Historical Studies''], '''10''' (1977), p. 231</ref> Following the Italian defeat in 1942, Abba Jobir was imprisoned again, and later given amnesty.
