A '''plantoid''' is a [[robot]] or [[synthetic biology|synthetic organism]] designed to look, act and grow like a plant. The concept was first scientifically published in 2010<ref name=mazzolai2010>{{Cite journal|doi=10.4161/psb.5.2.10457|last=Mazzolai|first=Barbara|title=The plant as a biomechatronic system|journal = Plant Signaling & Behavior|volume=5|issue=2|pages=90–93|publisher=[[Landes Bioscience]]|date=January 2010|ref=harv|pmc=2884106}}</ref> (although models of comparable systems controlled by neural networks date back to 2003<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nt.ntnu.no/users/skoge/prost/proceedings/adchem03/contents/paperpdf/poster/010.pdf|title=A robust iterative learning control with neural networks for robot|author1=Cheng Shao |author2=Juan Nie |author3=Furong Gao |publisher=Research Center of Information and Control, Dalian University of Technology| accessdate = 2010-10-11}}</ref>) and has so far remained largely theoretical. A prototype for the [[European Space Agency]] is now in development.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/science/discoveries/news/2007/10/veggie_intelligence|title=Smarty Plants: Inside the World's Only Plant-Intelligence Lab|author=Nicole Martinelli|publisher=Wired| accessdate = 2010-11-05|date=2007-10-30}}</ref>
A plantoid incorporates an inherently [[distributed computing#Architectures|distributed architecture]] consisting of autonomous and specialized modules. Modules can be modeled on plant parts such as the [[root cap]] and communicate to form a simple [[swarm intelligence]]. This kind of system may display great robustness and resilience. It is conjectured to be capable of energy harvesting and management, collective environmental awareness and many other functions.{{sfn|Mazzolai|2010|p= 93}}
In [[science fiction]], while human-like robots ([[Android (robot)|androids]]) are fairly frequent and animal-like biomorphic robots turn up occasionally, plantoids are quite rare. Exceptions occur in the novel ''Hearts, Hands and Voices'' (1992, US: ''The Broken Land'') by [[Ian McDonald (British author)|Ian McDonald]] and the TV series ''[[Jikuu Senshi Spielban]]''.
== History == In 2016 an autonomous plantoid was deployed to accept [[bitcoin]] donations and use them to pay artists to replicate it. It is a [[Decentralized autonomous organization|distributed autonomous organization]] (DAO). The plantoid was created by Primavera De Filippi, the founder of Okhaos, an art collective behind the effort, who is also a faculty associate at the [[Berkman Klein Center for Internet & Society|Berkman-Klein Center]] at Harvard University and a researcher at the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique|Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique]]. Self-executing software (a "[[smart contract]]") on the [[Blockchain (database)|blockchain]] automates the transactions. Donors vote to determine which artist (or group of artists) build the next version. The plantoid contracts with the artists and pays them as part of the contract. Earlier plantoid versions and their creators receive a portion of the donations from their descendants, creating a "[[multi-level marketing]]" incentive for each generation to have as many descendants as possible. The creators presume that more aesthetically attractive versions will attract more donations, creating an incentive for the artists to produce ever-more pleasing designs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://singularityhub.com/2016/12/21/this-bitcoin-eating-plant-robot-hires-artists-to-make-its-babies/|title=This Bitcoin-Eating Plant Robot Hires Artists to Make Its Babies|last=Frank|first=Aaron|date=2016-12-21|website=Singularity Hub|access-date=2016-12-22}}</ref>
