{{Infobox zoo | zoo_name = Sloth Sanctuary of Costa Rica | date_opened = 1997 | location = [[Limón Province]], [[Costa Rica]] | area = | coordinates = {{coord|9.799565|-82.915112 |display=inline}} | num_animals = | num_species = | website = [http://www.slothsanctuary.com/ slothsanctuary.com] }}
The '''Sloth Sanctuary of Costa Rica''' ({{lang-es|Santuario de Perezosos de Costa Rica}}) is a privately owned animal rescue center located near the city of [[Cahuita]]. The Sanctuary is dedicated to the rescue, rehabilitation, research, and release of injured or orphaned sloths.<ref name="about">{{cite web|title=ABOUT US|website=slothsanctuary.com|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref> Tours of the Sanctuary are offered to the public.
==History== After the [[1991 Limon earthquake]] ended their [[birding]] tourism business, Judy Avey-Arroyo and her husband Luis Arroyo built a hotel on their property.<ref name="dw">{{cite news|last1=Sevcenko|first1=Melanie|title=Sloth sanctuary nurtures animals back to health|url=http://www.dw.com/en/sloth-sanctuary-nurtures-animals-back-to-health/a-16750190|accessdate=1 January 2018|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]|date=17 April 2013}}</ref><ref name="about"/> In 1992, three girls brought the Arroyos an orphaned baby [[three-toed sloth]]. At the time, very little was known about sloth biology. By observing what the wild sloths on their property ate, the couple were able to hand-rear the sloth, named Buttercup, who still currently lives in the Sanctuary.<ref name="about"/><ref name="dw"/> In 1997, the Sanctuary was officially recognized as a rescue center, becoming Costa Rica's first sloth-only facility.<ref name="about"/>
The lives of the Sanctuary's sloth residents were documented in the 2013 [[Animal Planet]] television series, ''Meet the Sloths''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fendt|first1=Lindsay|title=Costa Rican Sloth Sanctuary featured on new Animal Planet series|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/2013/11/29/costa-rican-sloth-sanctuary-featured-on-new-animal-planet-series|accessdate=1 January 2018|work=[[The Tico Times]]|date=29 November 2013}}</ref> In 2016, two former employees accused the Sanctuary of animal mistreatment, which Avey-Arroyo denied.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schelling|first1=Ameena|title=Famous Sloth Sanctuary Is A Nightmare For Animals, Ex-Workers Say|url=https://www.thedodo.com/sloths-sanctuary-nightmare-1807794384.html/|accessdate=1 January 2018|work=[[The Dodo (website)|The Dodo]]|date=19 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Krumholtz|first1=Michael|title=Inside Costa Rica’s Sloth Sanctuary: Horror show or a solution to a complicated issue?|url=http://www.ticotimes.net/2016/08/01/sloth-sanctuary-costa-rica|accessdate=1 January 2018|work=The Tico Times|date=1 August 2016}}</ref>
