{{Okinawan name|Urasoe}}
{{nihongo|'''Urasoe ''[[Ueekata]]'' Chōri'''|浦添 親方 朝利|extra=? &ndash; 1638}}, also known by {{nihongo|'''Urasoe Jūri'''|浦添 重利}} and his Chinese style name {{nihongo|'''Shō Kakusen'''|向 鶴躚}}, was a bureaucrat of [[Ryukyu Kingdom]].

==Biography==
Urasoe Chōri was a son of [[Urasoe Chōshi]], and was also an younger brother of [[Kunigami Chōchi]]. He was elected as a member of ''[[Sanshikan]]'' in 1636.<ref>''[[Chūzan Seifu]]'', vol.8</ref><ref name=伝職年譜>[http://manwe.lib.u-ryukyu.ac.jp/d-archive/s/viewer?&cd=00030240 中山王府相卿伝職年譜　向祐等著写本]</ref>

==Disappearance==
A Spanish ship docked at [[Ishigaki Island]] in 1624. [[Juan de los Angeles Rueda]], who was a missionary of [[Dominican Order|O.P.]], preached to local people. Though [[Christianity]] was banned by [[Japan]] at that time, Rueda was sheltered by a local officer [[Ishigaki Eishō]] ({{lang|ja|石垣 永将}}). It was exposed in 1634, both Ishigaki and Rueda were exiled and later executed. This incident was known by [[Yaeyama Kirishitan Incident]] ({{lang|ja|八重山キリシタン事件}}).<ref>"[https://ryukyushimpo.jp/okinawa-dic/prentry-43178.html Yaeyama Kirishitan jiken]." ''Okinawa konpakuto jiten'' (沖縄コンパクト事典, "Okinawa Compact Encyclopedia").</ref> After this incident, Ryukyu started to investigate religious beliefs of its people, and forced Christians to convert (''[[Shūmon-aratame]]'' {{lang|ja|[[:ja:宗門改|宗門改]]}}). Urasoe Chōri went to [[Satsuma Domain|Satsuma]] to report the result of ''[[Shūmon-aratame]]'', but on the way home, his ship was caught in a storm and disappeared in the sea.<ref>''[[Chūzan Seifu]]'', appendix vol.1</ref> His position was vacant until 1641.<ref name=伝職年譜/>

