'''Gbadebowale Aboderin''' (1958 – 30 May 2018) was a Nigerian journalist, businessman and sports administrator, who was until his death the chairman of [[The Punch|Punch Nigeria Limited]], a publishing house founded by his father. Described by [[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard]] as a pillar of journalism,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2018/06/wale-aboderin-pillar-journalism-man-people/ |title=Wale Aboderin : Pillar of Journalism/Man of the people  |date=June 14, 2018 |website=Vanguard |access-date=2018-07-29}}</ref> he schooled at [[Government College, Ibadan]], before undergoing aviation training at Burnside-Ott Flying School. In sports, he was chairman, Lagos State Basketball Association and vice-president of Nigeria Basketball Supporters Club.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://thenationonlineng.net/wale-aboderin-1958-2018/ |title=Wale Aboderin (1958 – 2018) |last=Ojo |first=Mojirade |access-date=2018-07-29}}</ref> Aboderin died after a heart surgery in Lagos.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dailytrust.com.ng/punch-chairman-wale-aboderin-dies-at-60-253392.html |title=Punch chairman Wale Aboderin dies at 60 |website=Dailytrust |access-date=2018-07-29}}</ref> President of Nigeria, [[Muhammadu Buhari]], Governor of Lagos, [[Akinwunmi Ambode]] were among those that commiserated with his family.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://encomium.ng/buhari-mourns-wale-aboderin-chairman-punch-nigeria-limited/ |title=Buhari mourns Wale Aboderin, Chairman, Punch Nigeria Limited |date=June 1, 2018 |website=Encomium |access-date=2018-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://encomium.ng/ambode-condoles-with-punch-newspapers-over-death-of-chairman-aboderin/ |title=Ambode condoles with Punch newspapers over death of chairman, Aboderin |access-date=2018-07-29}}</ref>

In 1997, he established Nigeria's first private female basketball club, Dolphins.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://punchng.com/aboderin-man-who-changed-face-of-womens-basketball/ |title=Aboderin: Man who changed face of women’s basketball |website=Punch}}</ref>

